******
[1] Maine: pheasant
Date: Tue 29 Sep 2009
Source: Fosters.com [edited]
<http://www.fosters.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090929/GJNEWS_01/709299927>


Remainder of South Berwick pheasant flock killed by triple E is euthanized
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
After about 125 pheasants at a town farm died from eastern equine
encephalitis [EEE] in recent weeks, the rest of the flock was euthanized on
Monday [28 Sep 2009]. The move came on the same day the disease was
confirmed in a 2nd pheasant flock in York County.

About 80 pheasants at a farm in Parsonsfield recently died from EEE,
according to Scott Lindsay, a biologist for the Maine Department of Inland
Fisheries and Wildlife. The remaining 120 birds in the flock will be
euthanized today [29 Sep 2009], he said. About 125 pheasants at the South
Berwick farm were euthanized on Monday [28 Sep 2009]. Wildlife officials
declined to release the names of the farms, citing privacy concerns.

In both towns, the birds likely contracted the disease from an infected
mosquito and spread it in a cannibalistic manner -- a common behavior in
those birds, said Don Hoenig, state veterinarian for the agriculture
department.

The pheasants were brought to Maine as chicks and raised for hunting
purposes in a cooperative with the inland fisheries department and local
rod and gun clubs. Pheasant season begins on 1 Oct 2009, with 23 sites
available for public hunting during the rest of the month.

Hoenig said there has been an unusually large number of incidences of EEE
in animals this year [2009]. The disease has already killed 14 horses in 5
counties. Hoenig said in his 23 years in the agriculture department, he has
never seen the disease in pheasants.

The spread of the disease could be attributed to a combination of factors,
including a wet summer producing a bumper crop of mosquitoes, the
appearance of new migratory birds, and a lack of horses being vaccinated,
Hoenig said. As fall temperatures set in and frost occurs, incidences of
the disease should drop, he said.

Euthanizing the pheasants is a precautionary measure, wildlife officials
say, as the disease is deadly in both humans and animals. Mosquitoes carry
and transmit the disease to humans and animals through a bite. About a
third of people who contract the disease die, while the majority of
survivors have significant brain damage. There is no specific treatment for
EEE; care is based on symptoms.

The Maine Center for Disease Control and Prevention has urged people to
take typical precautions against mosquitoes to prevent EEE, including using
an insect repellent that contains DEET; wearing long clothing when
outdoors; limiting outdoor activities at dusk; and eliminating areas of
standing water, where mosquitoes thrive. Hoenig said horse owners should
inoculate the animals against the disease as well.

The discovery of EEE at the South Berwick farm is the 3rd recent incident
of the disease being found in the Seacoast region. A case in Rochester, NH,
was discovered after University of New Hampshire laboratory experiments
revealed the virus in 2 dead pet canaries.

City manager John Scruton declined to say where in the city the pets lived,
but said it was not around any schools or public playgrounds. In Dover, a
mosquito pool near Tolend Road tested positive for eastern equine
encephalitis, though the insects were of the melanura species, which only
feeds on birds and not humans.

The NH Department of Health and Human Services lists all of Rockingham
County as a high level risk area for EEE.

[byline: Jason Claffey]

