communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The state of Rhode Island in the New England region of the the US can be
located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://healthmap.org/r/00SV>. Tiverton and Little Compton are located in
Newport County (see county map at
<http://geology.com/county-map/rhode-island.shtml>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ

Eastern equine encephalitis virus (EEEV) is transmitted to humans by the
bite of an infected mosquito. Eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) is a rare
illness in humans, and only a few cases are reported in the United States
each year. Most cases occur in the Atlantic and Gulf Coast states. Most
persons infected with EEEV have no apparent illness. Severe cases of EEE
(involving encephalitis, an inflammation of the brain) begin with the
sudden onset of headache, high fever, chills, and vomiting. The illness may
then progress into disorientation, seizures, or coma.

EEE is one of the most severe mosquito-transmitted diseases in the United
States with approximately 33 per cent mortality and significant brain
damage in most survivors. There is no specific treatment for EEE; care is
based on symptoms. You can reduce your risk of being infected with EEEV by
using insect repellent, wearing protective clothing, and staying indoors
while mosquitoes are most active. If you think you or a family member may
have EEE, it is important to consult your healthcare provider for proper
diagnosis.

Pheasants are the one bird where EEE can be maintained in a cannibalistic
manner of pecking each other.

Interesting is the comment that mosquitoes reproduce in barns. It seems
mosquitoes require water and while there are water troughs in barns, most
of the troughs and buckets are clean and not stagnant reproduction pools.
While there are clearly barns that may benefit from a cleaning, it is
generally the exception not the rule with horse people. However, all horse
owners and stable mangers should promote and use vaccines to protect the
horses from EEE.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from
<http://www.cdc.gov/EasternEquineEncephalitis/>. - Mod.TG]
